(37, 1, NULL, 'Chapter 1.pptx.pdf', 'pdf', '# BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\n\n## CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION TO SOFTWARE MAINTENANCE\n\n### Introduction to Course Structure\n*   **Coursework – 60%**\n    *   a) Group Assignment (question will be delivered on week 1, week 5 submission) - 60%\n    *   b) Test (week 3) – 40%\n*   **Exam – 40%**\n\n### Software Evolution - Basic Concepts\n*   Understanding evolution in software is crucial, as systems adapt to new user demands and environmental changes.\n*   Complexity of software increases unless actively managed; feedback between users and maintenance teams is vital for guiding evolution.\n*   Adhering to sound maintenance processes, akin to agile development, supports successful system growth.\n\n### Software Systems Evolution\n*   Software evolution is the ongoing enhancement of software after its initial release to meet evolving stakeholder and market needs.\n*   Supporting additional functionalities, improving system performance, and allowing the system to run on a different operating system are among the goals.\n*   Essentially, as time passes, stakeholders and users have a better understanding of the system.\n*   “Over time, what evolves is not the software but our knowledge about a particular type of software”- Mehdi Jazayeri\n\n### Importance of Software Evolution\n*   Ensuring that the software product remains relevant and competitive.\n*   Enhances the overall user experience.\n*   Regular upgrades significantly increase usability and functionality, making software more efficient.\n*   Additionally, the system becomes increasingly stable, effectively reducing security risks and fortifying it against potential cyberattacks.\n    *   Source: https://qarea.com/blog/what-is-software-evolution-and-maintenance\n\n### Software Sustainment\n*   As modern systems grow more dependent on software, sustainment challenges also become more complicated. Overlooking these challenges may jeopardize the stability, improvement, and lifespan of systems in operation.\n*   Life-cycle sustainment factors involve supply, maintenance, transportation, sustaining engineering, data management, configuration management, Human Systems Integration (HSI), environmental and occupational health and safety (including explosives safety), protection of essential program information and anti-tamper measures, supportability, and interoperability.\n\n### Definition - Software Sustainment\n*   “The processes, procedures, people, material, and information required to support, maintain, and operate the software aspects of a system.” - SEI Working Definition\n\n### Criteria to Enter Software Sustainment (Lapham & Sei, 2014)\n*   **Stable software production baseline**—Sustainment organizations typically require software to be stable before they will accept it for ongoing maintenance.\n*   **Complete and current software documentation**—Having thorough and up-to-date software documentation is essential for the software sustainment team.\n*   **Authority to Operate (ATO) for an operational software system**—An Authority to Operate must be granted before any software system can be deemed operational in the field and eligible for sustainment.\n*   **Current and negotiated Sustainment Transition Plan**—Often, a program may have been developed, tested, and deemed operational, yet there may be no allocated funding for the creation and negotiation of the Sustainment Transition Plan.\n*   **Sustainment staffing and training plan**—It is crucial to properly staff the sustainment organization. The team should consist of trained software professionals who can collaborate with the development organization to ensure the necessary system knowledge is transferred.\n\n### Challenges of Sustainment (Lapham & Sei, 2014)\n*   Sustaining COTS (Commercial Off-The-Shelf) software involves addressing various factors such as system obsolescence, technology updates, source code escrow, and vendor license management, among other related aspects.\n*   Programmatic considerations highlight the challenges of categorizing sustainment needs as “minor requirements.”\n*   The transition to a sustainment phase examines elements like support database migration, the infrastructure for development and software support (including software testing labs, hardware spare parts, and procedures for releases), workforce needs, training for operations, and planning for the transition.\n*   User support covers topics such as help desk services, user manuals, and training for users.\n*   Information assurance addresses the specific challenges associated with IA in relation to COTS software products and the testing required for IA.\n\n### Software Maintenance - Basic Concepts\n*   Software maintenance is essential to ensure the long-term viability of software products throughout their lifecycle. i.e. from conception to completion.\n*   Changes to the software product are documented, the effects (impacts) of the changes are discovered, artefacts are modified, testing is performed, and a new software release is prepared.\n*   Users are educated, and assistance is available at all times.\n*   The term \"maintainer\" refers to a company or organisation that provides maintenance work.\n    *   Source: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n### Basic Concepts (Software Maintenance)\n*   Software maintenance aims to update and improve existing software efficiently while maintaining its integrity.\n*   It ensures that the software continues to function throughout its lifespan, adapts to changing user needs, and addresses issues that arise after deployment.\n*   The main objective is to extend the software’s useful life and postpone the need for replacement. Maintenance engineering uses established software engineering principles to systematically update operational software.\n*   Rigorous change management and regression testing prevent quality from declining. Additionally, maintenance offers ongoing user support, training, and monitors satisfaction.\n\n### Basic Concepts (Software Maintenance Costs and Design)\n*   Maintenance costs increase significantly in later life cycle stages, necessitating meticulous software engineering.\n*   Disciplined change control and testing are critical to mitigate system degradation from modifications.\n*   Conducting impact analysis is essential to limit unintended consequences.\n*   Designing maintainability into software helps make modifications manageable.\n*   Maintenance cost estimation should begin early in development planning, using historical data as a baseline.\n*   Estimates are refined with project progression and additional information.\n*   Categorizing costs reveals resource allocation, with most expenditures on enhancements rather than repairs.\n\n### Definition – Software Maintenance\n*   “The process of modifying a software system or component after delivery to correct faults, improve performance or other attributes, or adapt to a changed environment.” - IEEE Standard Glossary of Software Engineering Terminology\n\n### Reasons of Maintenance\n*   Prevent software operation from failure.\n*   Fix discovered software bugs.\n*   Improve software. Eg. to link or access to other new devices.\n*   Ensure software works in different environment (if required).\n*   Provide better experiences to users.\n*   Comply with organizational goal (if changes).\n\n### Software Development vs Software Maintenance\n\n| Feature                 | SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT                                                                    | SOFTWARE MAINTENANCE                                                                                      |\n| :---------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Driver**              | requirements driven                                                                     | event driven                                                                                              |\n| **Process Start**       | Process begins with the objective of designing and implementing a system to deliver certain functional and nonfunctional requirements. | scheduled in response to an event.                                                                        |\n| **Nature of Work**      | Primary/First Implementation.                                                           | on-going administration/support.                                                                          |\n| **Action**              | Development of software from new.                                                       | Modifying or adding new features based on existing software. (May include developing software)          |\n| **Outcome**             | Deliver new software.                                                                   | Prevent software from failure.                                                                            |\n\n### DevOps\n\n*   DevOps is a software development methodology that streamlines the delivery of high-performance applications by integrating and automating the work of development (Dev) and IT operations (Ops) teams, which traditionally functioned in silos. It promotes collaboration and coordination between these teams.\n*   Key features of DevOps include continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), allowing for smaller, faster software updates through frequent merging, testing, and deployment of new code. This approach evolves from agile software development, which emphasizes iterative processes over the traditional waterfall model that involves lengthy development and testing phases.\n*   Ultimately, DevOps focuses on meeting user demands for innovative features and consistent performance. - IBM\n\n### DevOps Life-Cycle\n*   Source: https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/devops\n\n#### Planning\n*   Teams identify new features and functions for upcoming releases, using user feedback and insights from internal stakeholders like engineers and compliance teams. The objective is to create a prioritized backlog of features, improvements, and bug fixes.\n\n#### Coding\n*   The DevOps team develops features from the backlog using common practices like test-driven development (TDD), pair programming, and peer code reviews. Code is initially written and tested on local workstations before advancing in the continuous delivery pipeline.\n*   Source: https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/devops\n\n#### Building\n*   New code is integrated into the existing code base, then tested and packaged for release. Automation plays a key role in merging, storing, and compiling code into executable files, with outputs saved in a binary repository for future use.\n\n#### Testing\n*   DevOps teams utilise automated testing throughout the development process, including unit tests during coding and linting after integration. Continuous testing allows for early detection of issues, implementing a \"shift-left\" approach.\n*   Source: https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/devops\n\n#### Release\n*   In the final workflow before user access, teams conduct thorough testing to ensure the software meets quality and security standards. Any identified defects are corrected before the application is launched into the production environment, often using automated processes.\n\n#### Deploy\n*   The updated application moves to a production environment, initially deployed to a subset of users to verify stability before a full rollout.\n*   Source: https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/devops\n\n#### Operate\n*   DevOps teams ensure new features are functioning correctly with no service interruptions, employing automated tools for continuous monitoring and optimisation of operations.\n\n#### Monitor\n*   Feedback from users and insights from previous workflows are collected to improve future processes and inform planning for the next release of new features.\n*   Source: https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/devops\n\n### DevOps Culture\n*   The DevOps culture emphasises collaboration, communication, and automation among all stakeholders involved in software delivery, including development, IT operations, compliance, and security teams.\n*   It requires continuous interaction and shared responsibility to foster innovation and prioritise quality from the outset. At a technical level, DevOps leverages automated tools for testing, deployment, and infrastructure provisioning to enhance project delivery and minimise errors.\n*   Feedback and measurement are essential for optimising processes and improving software quality. To implement a DevOps culture, organisations often need to dismantle silos and form cross-functional teams that manage projects from start to finish, promoting accountability and collaboration in alignment with agile practices.\n    *   Source: https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/devops\n\n### DevOps and Maintenance\n*   One of the most significant—yet often overlooked—impacts of the DevOps movement is its effort to make software maintenance appealing again. DevOps not only offers better organisational support for software maintenance but also enhances communication between developers and operations teams, leading to more effective maintenance strategies.\n*   A fundamental principle of DevOps is the \"you build it, you own it\" philosophy, which asserts that the developers who create code are also responsible for its deployment and ongoing maintenance. Even if the organisation doesn’t fully embrace this principle, it likely fosters increased collaboration between developers and IT operations. Consequently, when production issues arise or upgrades are necessary for maintaining reliability, developers are actively involved in resolving these matters.\n*   Source: https://devops.com/making-software-maintenance-cool-devops/\n\n### DevOps and Maintenance (Perception and Integration)\n*   Despite the focus on software maintenance in practice, conversations about maintenance tasks remain infrequent in the DevOps arena. Coding continues to be celebrated as the most exciting aspect of work within this field. While DevOps has succeeded in connecting those who code with those who maintain, it hasn’t yet made maintenance itself a more attractive aspect of the job.\n*   This perception may need to evolve. Organizations that are ahead of the curve should acknowledge that software maintenance—which encompasses activities like applying updates, monitoring applications, and scaling infrastructure—is just as critical for ensuring a smooth application experience as the software itself. This recognition should be explicitly integrated into the DevOps approach.\n*   Source: https://devops.com/making-software-maintenance-cool-devops/\n\n## References\n\n*   Blokdyk. G. ((2020). Maintenance of software : a complete guide : practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\n*   Blokdyk. G.. (2020). Software change management : a complete guide : practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\n*   Maxim. B. R., Pressman. R. S. (2020) Software Engineering: A Practitioner\'s Approach. 9th Edn. McGraw-Hill Education\n\n### Other references\n*   E. Varga. (2017). Unraveling software maintenance and evolution : thinking outside the box. Springer.\n*   F. Tsui. O. Karam. B. Bernal. (2018). Essentials of Software Engineering. 4th Edition. Jones & Bartlett Learning.\n*   Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n*   Cook, S. , Harrison, R. , Lehman, M.M. , Wernick, P. , 2006. Evolution in software systems: foundations of the spe classification scheme. J. Softw. Maintenance 18 (1), 1–35 .\n*   http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n*   T. Mens, M. Wermelinger, S. Ducasse, S. Demeyer, R. Hirschfeld and M. Jazayeri, \"Challenges in software evolution,\" Eighth International Workshop on Principles of Software Evolution (IWPSE\'05), 2005, pp. 13-22, doi: 10.1109/IWPSE.2005.7.\n*   Lapham, M., & Sei. (2014). LEGACY SYSTEM SOFTWARE SUSTAINMENT . https://apps.dtic.mil/sti/tr/pdf/ADA591337.pdf', 'user_upload/1/content/c7651368-460e-406e-bb80-8b6cc59edde8.pdf', '2025-11-12'),
