rs to those items that provide control over the activity.*\\n*   **Metrics:** *This refers to the items that are measured during the execution of the activity.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n## ISO\\/IEC 14764 Maintenance Process\\n\\nAbran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9)*.\\n\\n### ISO\\/IEC 14764 Maintenance Process High-Level Activities\\n\\n*The maintenance process comprises the following high-level activities:*\\n\\n1.  Process implementation\\n2.  Problem and modification analysis\\n3.  Modification implementation\\n4.  Maintenance review and acceptance\\n5.  Migration\\n6.  Retirement\\n\\nAbran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9)*.\\n\\n#### Process Implementation\\n\\n*   *Create maintenance processes and strategies.*\\n*   *Procedures for Modification Requests should be established.*\\n*   *Put the CM process into action.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Problem and Modification Analysis\\n\\n*   *Perform a preliminary investigation.*\\n*   *Confirm the issue.*\\n*   *Create choices for executing the change.*\\n*   *Keep track of the outcomes.*\\n*   *Obtain clearance for the option of modification.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Implement Modification\\n\\n*   *Conduct a thorough investigation (analysis).*\\n*   *The modification should be developed, coded, and tested.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Maintenance Review and Acceptance\\n\\n*   *Conduct evaluations.*\\n*   *Obtain approval for the change.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Migration\\n\\n*   *Ascertain that the migration is compliant with ISO\\/IEC 12207.*\\n*   *Make a migration strategy.*\\n*   *Users should be notified about migration intentions.*\\n*   *Carry out processes in parallel.*\\n*   *Notify the user that the transfer has begun.*\\n*   *Conduct a post-op evaluation.*\\n*   *Make sure that old data can be accessed.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Retirement\\n\\n*   *Develop a plan for retirement.*\\n*   *Acknowledge users of retirement plans.*\\n*   *Parallel operations are conducted.*\\n*   *Acknowledge user the start of retirement.*\\n*   *Make sure old data is accessible.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n## Maintenance Models\\n\\n### Reuse-Oriented Models\\n\\n1.  Quick fix model\\n2.  Iterative enhancement model\\n3.  Full reuse model\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Reuse-Oriented Models\\n\\n*Assumes that existing components can be re-used in software maintenance. It consists of the following steps:*\\n\\n*   *Identifying the components of the old system which can be reused*\\n*   *Understanding these components*\\n*   *Modifying the old system components so that they can be used in the new system*\\n*   *Integrating the modified components into the new system.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Quick Fix Model\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n##### Quick Fix Model Description\\n\\n*   *Necessary changes are quickly made to the code and then to the accompanying documentation.*\\n*   *The new code is recompiled to produce a new version.*\\n*   *Embodies a commonly used approach to software maintenance.*\\n*   *Low cost.*\\n*   *Less concern on the impacts of modifications.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n#### Iterative Enhancement Model\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n##### Iterative Enhancement Model Description\\n\\n*   *Based on the Japanese concept of Kaizen, which stands for the gradual and systematic enhancement of procedures.*\\n*   *First changes are made to the highest level documents.*\\n*   *Eventually, changes are propagated down to the code level.*\\n*   *Assumes complete documentation is available.*\\n*   *It begins with the existing system’s artifacts, namely, requirements, design, code, test, and analysis documents.*\\n*   *It revises the highest-level documents affected by the changes and propagates the changes down through the lower-level documents.*\\n*   *The model allows maintainers to redesign the system, based on the analysis of the existing system.*\\n*   *Also accommodates the quick fix model.*\\n\\nThree stages cycle:\\n\\n*   *Analysis of software system.*\\n*   *Classification of requested modifications.*\\n*   *Implementation of requested modifications.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n#### Full Reuse Model\\n\\n*   *A new system is built from components of the old system and others available in the repository.*\\n*   *The main assumption in this model is the availability of a repository of artifacts describing the earlier versions of the present and similar systems.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n##### Full Reuse Model Activities\\n\\n*Full reuse comprises two major steps:*\\n\\n1.  *Perform requirement analysis and design of the new system.*\\n2.  *Use the appropriate artifacts, such as requirements, design, code, and test from any earlier versions of the old system.*\\n\\nThe following activities are performed:\\n\\n*   *Identify the components of the old system that are candidates for reuse.*\\n*   *Understand the identified system components.*\\n*   *Modify the old system components to support the new requirements.*\\n*   *Integrate the modified components to form the newly developed system.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Other Models\\n\\n*   Boehm\'s Model\\n*   Taute Maintenance Model.\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n## References\\n\\n1.  Blokdyk. G. (2020). *Maintenance of software: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment*. Art of Service.\\n2.  Blokdyk. G. (2020). *Software change management: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment*. Art of Service.\\n3.  Maxim. B. R., Pressman. R. S. (2020) *Software Engineering: A Practitioner\'s Approach*. 9th Edn. McGraw-Hill Education.\\n4.  E. Varga. (2017). *Unraveling software maintenance and evolution: thinking outside the box*. Springer.\\n5.  F. Tsui. O. Karam. B. Bernal. (2018). *Essentials of Software Engineering*. 4th Edition. Jones & Bartlett Learning.\\n6.  Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n7.  Abran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9)*. 10.13140\\/RG.2.2.12202.44489.\\n8.  Gupta, A., Xavier, S., & Sharma, S. (n.d.). Software Maintenance: Challenges and Issues. https:\\/\\/www.ijcse.net\\/docs\\/IJCSE15-04-01-037.pdf\"}', 'Software Maintenance: Processes and Challenges', NULL, '2025-11-15 09:04:22'),
(41, 2000000044, '{\"markdown\":\"# Planning for Disaster\\n\\n## 1. Introduction\\n### AWS Academy Cloud Architecting\\n### Planning for Disaster\\n\\n## 2. Module Objectives\\n### Identify disaster planning strategies including RPO and RTO\\n### Identify disaster planning for AWS service categories\\n### Describe common DR patterns and implementation\\n### Use AWS Well-Architected Framework principles for DR\\n\\n## 3. Module Overview\\n### Presentation Sections\\n#### Disaster planning strategies\\n#### AWS disaster recovery planning\\n#### Disaster recovery patterns\\n#### Applying AWS Well-Architected Framework principles\\n### Knowledge Checks\\n#### 10-question knowledge check\\n#### Sample exam question\\n\\n## 4. Hands-on Labs in this Module\\n### Guided Lab\\n#### Configuring Hybrid Storage and Migrating Data with AWS Storage Gateway S3 File Gateway\\n\\n## 5. Role of a Cloud Architect in Disaster Planning\\n### Mitigate risk and support timely recovery\\n### Consider business needs and balance cost, data loss, and recovery time\\n\\n## 6. Disaster Planning Strategies\\n### Failures Can Occur at Any Scale\\n#### Small-scale events\\n#### Large-scale events\\n#### Global events\\n### Avoiding and Planning for Disaster\\n#### Fault tolerance\\n#### Backup\\n#### Disaster recovery\\n### Factors That Influence Disaster Planning Strategies\\n#### Time dependency\\n#### Data loss\\n#### Geographic location\\n#### Cost\\n### Determining RPO (Recovery Point Objective)\\n#### Maximum acceptable amount of data loss (measured in time)\\n#### Example: Determining RPO\\n##### Acceptable loss of 800 records\\n##### 100 records created per hour\\n##### RPO of 8 hours acceptable\\n### Determining RTO (Recovery Time Objective)\\n#### Maximum acceptable time for business process to remain out of commission\\n#### Example: Determining RTO\\n##### Ticketing service restoration within 2 hours\\n##### Revenue loss after 2 hours outage\\n##### RTO of 2 hours acceptable\\n### Preparing a BCP (Business Continuity Plan)\\n#### System of prevention and recovery from threats\\n#### Components:\\n##### Business impact analysis\\n##### Risk assessment\\n##### Disaster recovery plan\\n##### Determined RPO and RTO\\n### Key Takeaways: Disaster Planning Strategies\\n#### Failures occur at any scale\\n#### DR plan limits impact\\n#### RPO: max acceptable data loss\\n#### RTO: max acceptable downtime\\n#### BCP includes RPO and RTO\\n\\n## 7. AWS Disaster Recovery Planning\\n### DR Plans Span More Than One Region\\n### Storage and Backup Building Blocks\\n#### On-premises data center\\n#### AWS Cloud\\n### Configuring Cross-Region Replication\\n### EBS Volume Snapshots\\n### File System Replication\\n### Recovering Compute Infrastructure\\n#### Custom AMIs (Golden AMIs)\\n#### Custom container images\\n#### Auto Scaling group\\n#### Amazon Elastic Container Service cluster\\n### Harnessing EventBridge for Regional Failover\\n### Designing for Resiliency and Recovery\\n#### Route 53\\n#### ELB (Elastic Load Balancing)\\n#### Amazon VPN\\n#### AWS Direct Connect\\n### Supporting Database Recovery\\n#### Amazon RDS\\n##### Save snapshot in separate Region\\n##### Use read replicas and Multi-AZ\\n##### Retain automated backups\\n#### DynamoDB\\n##### Back up entire tables\\n##### Point-in-time-recovery\\n##### Use global tables\\n### Replicating and Redeploying Environments\\n#### CloudFormation\\n#### OpsWorks\\n### Key Takeaways: AWS Disaster Recovery Planning\\n#### Use CRR, EBS snapshots, RDS snapshots for data protection\\n#### Use Route 53 and ELB for application availability\\n#### Use CloudFormation for automated environment deployment\\n#### Use EventBridge for automatic data restore and failover\\n\\n## 8. Disaster Recovery Patterns\\n### Common Disaster Recovery Patterns on AWS\\n#### Backup and restore\\n#### Pilot light\\n#### Warm standby\\n#### Multi-site\\n### Backup and Restore Pattern\\n### AWS Storage Gateway Backup and Restore Pattern\\n### Implementing Backup and Restore\\n#### Preparation phase\\n##### Create backups, store in S3, document procedures\\n#### In case of disaster\\n##### Retrieve backups, restore infrastructure, restore system, route traffic\\n### Pilot Light Pattern\\n### Implementing Pilot Light Pattern\\n#### Preparation phase\\n##### Replicate servers, create AMIs, test regularly\\n#### In case of disaster\\n##### Bring up resources, scale system, switch over\\n### Warm Standby Pattern\\n### Implementing Warm Standby Pattern\\n#### Preparation phase\\n##### Similar to pilot light, all components running, continuous testing\\n#### In case of disaster\\n##### Failover critical load, scale system further\\n### Multi-Site Pattern\\n### Implementing Multi-Site Pattern\\n#### Preparation phase\\n##### Similar to warm standby, full scaling, consider licensing cost\\n#### In case of disaster\\n##### Immediately failover all production load\\n### Summary of Common DR Patterns\\n#### Backup and restore\\n##### Cost: Lower, RTO\\/RPO: Hours, Use Cases: Lower priority\\n#### Pilot light\\n##### Cost: Medium, RTO\\/RPO: 10s of minutes, Use Cases: Core services\\n#### Warm standby\\n##### Cost: Higher, RTO\\/RPO: Minutes, Use Cases: Business-critical services\\n#### Multi-site\\n##### Cost: Highest, RTO\\/RPO: Near real-time, Use Cases: Automatic failover\\n### Practice Game Day Exercises\\n#### Ensure backups\\/snapshots\\/AMIs work\\n#### Monitor monitoring system\\n#### Establish and improve RTO\\/RPO\\n### Key Takeaways: Disaster Recovery Patterns\\n#### Common patterns: Backup and restore, Pilot light, Warm standby, Multi-site\\n#### Backup and restore: most cost-effective, highest RTO\\n#### Multi-site: fastest RTO, highest cost\\n#### Storage Gateway for hybrid backup\\/recovery\\n\\n## 9. Guided Lab: Configuring Hybrid Storage and Migrating Data with AWS Storage Gateway S3 File Gateway (AWS Storage Gateway Lab)\\n### AWS Storage Gateway Lab Tasks\\n#### Configure S3 File Gateway with NFS\\n#### Migrate data to S3 bucket\\n#### Configure primary and secondary S3 buckets\\n#### Create S3 lifecycle policy\\n### Debrief: AWS Storage Gateway Lab\\n#### Cross-Region replication configuration\\n#### AMI selection for File Gateway\\n\\n## 10. Applying AWS Well-Architected Framework Principles to Disaster Planning\\n### Well-Architected Framework Best Practices for Planning for Disasters\\n### Best Practice Approach: Failure Management – Plan for Disaster Recovery\\n#### Define recovery objectives (downtime, data loss)\\n#### Use defined recovery strategies\\n#### Test disaster recovery implementation\\n### Best Practice Approach: Operate – Manage Workload and Operations Events\\n#### Define customer communication plan for outages\\n### Best Practice Approach: Identity and Access Management – Permissions Management\\n#### Establish emergency access process\\n### Key Takeaways: Applying AWS Well-Architected Framework Principles to Disaster Planning\\n#### Define recovery objectives (downtime, data loss)\\n#### Use defined recovery strategies\\n#### Test DR implementation\\n#### Define customer communication plan\\n#### Establish emergency access process\\n\\n## 11. Module Wrap-up\\n### Module Summary\\n#### Covered disaster planning strategies (RPO\\/RTO)\\n#### Covered AWS service categories for DR\\n#### Covered common DR patterns and implementation\\n#### Covered AWS Well-Architected Framework principles for DR\\n### Considerations for the Cafe\\n#### Advise café based on cloud architect concerns\\n### Module Knowledge Check\\n#### Online knowledge check, 10 questions\\n#### Retakeable\\n### Sample Exam Question\\n#### Business-critical apps, 7 min data loss, functional version for immediate majority traffic, scale over time, most cost-effective.\\n#### Key words: Business-critical, Functional version, Majority of traffic immediately, Cost-effective\\n### Sample Exam Question: Response Choices\\n#### A: Backup and restore\\n#### B: Pilot light\\n#### C: Warm standby\\n#### D: Multi-site\\n### Sample Exam Question: Answer\\n#### C: Warm standby\\n\\n## 12. Thank You\\n### Contact support for corrections, feedback, or questions: https:\\/\\/support.aws.amazon.com\\/#\\/contacts\\/aws-academy\"}', 'AWS Disaster Recovery Planning', NULL, '2025-11-19 07:20:18');

